

Method 2: Cross-Compilation (On a Linux Host PC)

This is the preferred professional method. It assumes your host development PC is running Ubuntu/Debian.
1. Install the Toolchain on your Host PC
Bash

sudo apt update
sudo apt install build-essential gcc-arm-linux-gnueabihf git

2. Get the BeagleBone Kernel Source

You must compile against the exact kernel version running on your BBB. Check your BBB version with uname -r on the board. Assuming it is a standard 5.x or 4.x TI kernel:
Bash

git clone https://github.com/beagleboard/linux.git --depth=1 -b <your-bbb-kernel-branch>
cd linux
export ARCH=arm
export CROSS_COMPILE=arm-linux-gnueabihf-
make bb.org_defconfig
make modules_prepare

3. Compile Your Driver on the Host PC

Navigate to your driver source directory and create this Makefile:
Makefile

obj-m += platform_char.o
# Path to the BBB kernel source tree you downloaded above
KDIR ?= /path/to/cloned/linux 

all:
	$(MAKE) -C $(KDIR) M=$(PWD) ARCH=arm CROSS_COMPILE=arm-linux-gnueabihf- modules

clean:
	$(MAKE) -C $(KDIR) M=$(PWD) ARCH=arm CROSS_COMPILE=arm-linux-gnueabihf- clean

Run make to build the platform_char.ko file, then copy it to your BeagleBone Black using scp:
Bash

scp platform_char.ko debian@beaglebone.local:/home/debian/

Testing the Driver on the BeagleBone Black

Once platform_char.ko is on your BeagleBone Black, run these commands to test it:
1. Load the Module
Bash

sudo insmod platform_char.ko

2. Verify Module Insertion and Kernel Logs

Check dmesg to ensure the driver initialized, the platform device matched, and the character device was created successfully:
Bash

dmesg | tail -n 15

You should see output similar to:

    basic_pchar: module init

    basic_pchar: allocated major=240 minor=0

    basic_pchar: probe called

    basic_pchar: created /dev/pchar0 with major=240 minor=0

    basic_pchar: platform device registered

Verify that the device node and sysfs class exist:
Bash

ls -l /dev/pchar0
ls -d /sys/class/pchar_class/

3. Test Read and Write Operations

By default, the device permissions might restrict standard users. Give it global access or use sudo:
Bash

sudo chmod 666 /dev/pchar0

Write data into the driver:
Bash

echo "Hello BeagleBone Black!" > /dev/pchar0

Read data back out:
Bash

cat /dev/pchar0

(It should print Hello BeagleBone Black!)

Check dmesg again to watch your pchar_open, pchar_write, pchar_read, and pchar_release functions work in sequence:
Bash

dmesg | tail -n 10

4. Unload the Module

When you are done testing, clean up and remove the module:
Bash

sudo rmmod platform_char
dmesg | tail -n 5

(You will see the exit and remove logs indicating /dev/pchar0 has been safely destroyed).
